Talk to your sleep
Some children talk during the night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very excited to tell us something that happened to them the previous day, but to those children who speak are still asleep.
The first time it happens, at most you take a scare, but it doesn't really matter very much.
This is a benign change in the defined sleepiness.
It occurs with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Certainly, most of you have told me that you have spoken in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur in a very sporadic way (once in life, for example, associated with a high fever episode) or with a greater regularity (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child remembers nothing anymore.
There is no single reason to explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes episodes are linked to other sleep disorders such as incubation, night fear, night enuresis (to make the pipe to bed), or sleepbullism, but not necessarily so.
As noted above, it can be associated with very high fever stages, stress situations or overcrowding.
In any case, it is a phenomenon that is not yet studied.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
It may happen that the person speaks with a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite happens (urla, shouting, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, you should observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to check whether there are any issues that are generating an abnormal state of anxiety as a result of the situation.
We have said that this is benign alteration, so there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, if combined with insomnia or stress).
What can be done, on the other hand, is to take into account a series of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before he goes to sleep.
Offer quiet games and avoid TV programs or series that cause fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for whom it is difficult to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire some inner calm.
This will allow the child to sleep more quietly.
Once the dreams appear, try to keep calm.
