Hema-Québec celebrated yesterday the tenth anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. FrancineDécary, had every reason to rejoice, because Hema-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, he has regained the confidence of the public, seriously removed from the scandal of the blood infection between 1980 and 1990.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected by the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
In the face of such a drama and the protests of the population, the Government of Canada conducted a public investigation in February 1994, led by Judge Horace Krever, which sought to highlight the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to disseminate recommendations to prevent the recurrence of such a disaster.
While Judge Krever was delaying a relationship, some provinces set up a committee with the aim of designing a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the reports of Gélineau et Krever, two suppliers were created in Canada: Hema-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society (Canada Blood Society) for all other provinces and territories.
In 1998, when Hema-Québec started its activities, 38% of the people said that they still had confidence in the system of donations in Quebec, Dr. Decary recalled.
The situation was deadly.
Thanks to continued efforts to improve the safety of blood collection and field research over the years, we have regained public confidence," he said before saying proudly that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the Québec population now had confidence in Hema-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary is convinced that "trust is something extremely fragile".
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were many cases in Europe of the human variant of the mad cow, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob's morbidity, which has been in the presidency since 1998, the year of the foundation.
"And we didn't know at all if that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
It is therefore based on one of the main recommendations of Krever and Gélinau's reports, according to which when you have doubts and could get a serious disease, in this case the morgue of Creutzfeldt-Jakob, which manifests itself with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, is taken of exclusion measures.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than one month in the United Kingdom was rejected from 1980.
Now, for a few years, it has been shown that without a doubt this disease is transmitted through infected blood.
This episode has shown us so that it has made sense to apply the precautionary principle."
In 1999 a much more efficient technique for HIV identification appeared on the market: nuclear acid tests (TANs) that enable donors to directly recognise the presence of the virus in the blood and not the presence of antibodies against it, on which the tests used so far were based.
The TANs have allowed to reduce the window period, i.e. since the person contracted the disease to what the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, the specialist explains.
That period could be reduced to less than one week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and not being able to detect them is thus significantly reduced.
These improvements have led to a significant reduction in the risk of anti-AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, a person of 12 million is at risk of receiving blood infected by the HIV virus.
"In other words, this means that it will be necessary to distribute 12 million blood samples before someone is infected by the HIV virus.
Since Hema-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500 000 blood samples each year, there will be more than 24 years before a case of HIV has been transmitted with a transfusion.
I believe that today we can feel calm in receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health, says the head of the Hema-Quebec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than a year ago, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the Réunion Island, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted to the blood by an insect.
It must be constantly vigilant", continues Dr.Sa Décary before stressing that in addition to having safe resources, Hema-Quebec must also provide sufficient resources.
"The needs are increasing because the population is getting older.
Being the most aggressive cancer cures, patients often need a contribution of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the number of donors that on average constitute only 3% of Quebec's inhabitants acceptable as donors."
However, all healthy persons who have attained 18 years of age and who meet the eligibility criteria can give blood every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of the people who offer themselves as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a country where the latter is disseminated, they will be rejected for a period equal to one year.
"With this 3% we can keep an inventory capable of responding to the needs of hospitals.
