Neurologists and economists researchers at the University of New York have been able to discover the neuro-economic bases of this well-known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to their study published on Science magazine, men do not want to stay back in a race such as the eBay auction, so they are also available to pay a higher price.
The research has tried to trace the nervous scheme of this "lot" at the level of the nervous system through experimental axes.
One group of volunteers played the game, the other group of players participated in an auction, while the functional magnetic resonance method (fMRI) examined the active areas of the brain of the participants in the experiment.
In both games participants could win money, but in the game of auction, where the essential element is to bid more than the other, the body stretched under the brain cortex becomes intensively functioning when you lose the game.
This brain area, in addition to other functions, plays a role in the "self-gratification" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to researchers, the rise in the price is explained by scanning the actual reaction of the broken body.
In support of their theory, the research group economists conducted a financial investigation.
In this investigation, three groups have appealed against a partner under different conditions.
The control group reported the actual value of the product concerned and made their point.
In addition to this, another group have promised that in the event of a win, they will receive another $15 prize.
The third group would have received 15 dollars before the auction, but the members of the group would have lost the money in the event of a loss at the auction.
The difference between the two groups consisted in the fact that for one of them the gain was underlined, while for the other the loss.
Testing the hypothesis of neurologists, the group members who played "against loss" were willing to make higher points of the control group or "wine".
"These results are not deductible from any of the previously existing economic theories.
In fact, these so far explained the phenomena that are likely to be at stake with the joy of winning and avoiding the risk.
