Hepatitis: when should you contact your doctor?
Almost half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, but chronic liver diseases are mentioned in Hungary among the first causes of death.
In Hungary the number of hepatitis patients goes up to one hundred thousand, of which only 7000 are treated: the reason is that many patients do not know how to be infected.
The liver definition is the collective name of the infectious liver diseases caused by several viruses.
There are many similarities between symptoms, typical are hepatitis and itteracy, but their pathogens and diseases differ from one another.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen agent: hepatitis A and E through the food channel (e.g. water and infected foods), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal loss, salt).
For those travelling, vaccination against the A and B virus is useful, against C there is no vaccine.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after the consumption of infected foods, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After forming yellow spots on the skin and on the white of the eyes, the faeces become clear and the dark urine, the healing takes place within two or three weeks.
A million people die every year worldwide for hepatitis B, the most severe variant of the disease, causing liver tumors and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason is, according to the estimates, that only one person in ten receives a pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if it is not cured it may cause liver cirrhosis and liver tumours.
Most of the infected people do not know that they have contracted the disease because pathogens destroy the liver cells in a subtle way, in many cases the first symptoms occur after 20-30 years.
Therefore, it is very important to prevent and carry out regular medical tests.
This disease is much more common than the average in three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts and tattoos.
In the world today, the number of people infected by chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
Because also a routine laboratory examination reveals the disease is worth addressing the doctor of the family when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
In time, the disease is cured, the virus can be eliminated from the body, so it stops the infectious power and can prevent tumor formation.
On September 30, it is the world's day of hepatitis, organized for the first time in 2004 worldwide by disease associations.
The aim is to draw attention to chronic hepatitis, its causes for development and early recognition of disease.
